VARIABLES AND DATA TYPES:
In Python, variables are used to store data, and data types define the kind of data a variable can hold.

--> Variables in Python:
A variable is created by assigning a value using the = operator.

➤ Syntax:
variable_name = value

➤ Examples:
x = 5          # Integer
name = "Sri"  # String
pi = 3.14      # Float
is_valid = True  # Boolean

• Python is dynamically typed — you don’t need to declare the type of a variable explicitly.
• Variable names are case-sensitive (Name and name are different).

--> Basic Data Types in Python:
Data Type	              Description	                        Example
int	                    Integer numbers	                    x = 10
float	                  Decimal numbers	                    pi = 3.14
str	                    Text / string data	                name = "Sravya"
bool	                  Boolean (True/False)	              is_happy = True
list	                  Ordered, mutable collection	        fruits = ["orange", "kiwi"]
tuple	                  Ordered, immutable collection	      coordinates = (4, 5)
dict	                  Key-value pairs	                    person = {"name": "Sri", "age": 18}
set	                    Unordered, unique items	            unique_nums = {1, 2, 3}
NoneType	              Represents absence of value	        x = None

• Type Checking:
  You can check the type of any variable using the type() function.

➤ Example:
x = 42
print(type(x))  # <class 'int'>

• Type Conversion (Casting):
  You can convert between types using built-in functions.

➤ Example:
x = int("10")      # Convert string to int
y = str(3.14)      # Convert float to string
z = float(5)       # Convert int to float
